00:11:49,462 --> 00:11:51,943
to get a sense of depth and people were having a hard time

248
00:11:52,003 --> 00:11:54,704
seeing when they dropped the box where it was going to land. So

249
00:11:54,724 --> 00:11:57,765
they said why don't you add shadows to the box. So I said

250
00:11:57,825 --> 00:12:00,386
okay, I added a directional light so that you can, you know,

251
00:12:00,406 --> 00:12:02,627
there are shadows. And then people were asking, well, where

252
00:12:02,647 --> 00:12:07,228
is the light coming from? So I said okay, I'll add windows to,

253
00:12:07,608 --> 00:12:10,409
you know, provide an explanation for the source of the light. And

254
00:12:10,449 --> 00:12:12,890
as a result of the window, people were able to see the

255
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:13,310
outside.

256
00:12:14,353 --> 00:12:16,734
This wasn't intentional on my part. I just built a bunch of

257
00:12:16,874 --> 00:12:21,195
rooms together in one scene. However, everybody was very

258
00:12:21,215 --> 00:12:23,916
excited about what was going on outside and they were asking,

259
00:12:24,076 --> 00:12:26,897
hey, can I go outside? And originally I didn't want the

260
00:12:26,937 --> 00:12:29,537
player to because it would add all this complexity, but

261
00:12:29,577 --> 00:12:32,658
everybody kept asking for it, so I allowed them to go outside.

262
00:12:32,678 --> 00:12:35,499
This was also at a time when I introduced the edge detection

263
00:12:35,539 --> 00:12:35,819
shader.

264
00:12:37,199 --> 00:12:39,440
Now this of course introduced the problem of players falling

265
00:12:39,500 --> 00:12:43,301
off the world. And the one thing I did not want to do was I

266
00:12:43,661 --> 00:12:46,342
didn't want to add invisible colliders. Because there are

267
00:12:46,362 --> 00:12:48,643
some games that have it and it's very frustrating. You want to

268
00:12:48,663 --> 00:12:50,523
explore and it's constantly preventing you from going to

269
00:12:50,543 --> 00:12:54,245
places. And I also wanted everything you can see in the

270
00:12:54,265 --> 00:12:56,786
world that you can get to. Because I remember playing Sky

271
00:12:56,806 --> 00:12:59,526
Rim and one of the most magical moments in that game is when you

272
00:12:59,546 --> 00:13:02,367
see a mountain in the distance and then later on you're

273
00:13:02,487 --> 00:13:05,308
actually on that mountain. So...

274
00:13:06,899 --> 00:13:09,421
So I couldn't put anything in the sky, because that meant I'd

275
00:13:09,461 --> 00:13:10,922
have to create additional content.

276
00:13:12,544 --> 00:13:15,186
And I got this problem of a very blank sky, which is very

277
00:13:15,226 --> 00:13:18,789
boring, and I added a skybox, and it just looked absolutely

278
00:13:18,829 --> 00:13:19,209
terrible.

279
00:13:20,630 --> 00:13:22,812
However, at some point I realized that by introducing

280
00:13:23,052 --> 00:13:25,154
3D world wrapping, I've sort of solved all those problems,

281
00:13:25,214 --> 00:13:27,796
because now I can have things in the sky, and it's not new

282
00:13:27,836 --> 00:13:30,398
content, and I can allow the player to get there.

283
00:13:31,339 --> 00:13:33,220
And yeah, it's not new content, because it's the

284
00:13:33,260 --> 00:13:33,660
same thing.

285
00:13:34,921 --> 00:13:36,442
So it solves the blank sky problem.

286
00:13:37,062 --> 00:13:39,563
It ensures that everything you can see is still a place that

287
00:13:39,583 --> 00:13:40,183
you can get to.

288
00:13:40,824 --> 00:13:43,005
And it's also just a much more interesting level in general.

289
00:13:43,025 --> 00:13:46,686
So these are some of the early screenshots of the game when I

290
00:13:46,726 --> 00:13:47,707
introduced world wrapping.

291
00:13:47,987 --> 00:13:49,007
And this is one of the earliest

292
00:13:49,027 --> 00:13:50,268
implementations in motion.

293
00:13:53,069 --> 00:13:55,330
It is very slow here, but you can see.

294
00:13:56,973 --> 00:13:59,695
in this case you've got the button, you press it, it drops

295
00:13:59,735 --> 00:14:04,778
a box, and then you jump off the ledge. And what you'll notice

296
00:14:04,818 --> 00:14:08,040
in this implementation is that the distance between instances

297
00:14:08,100 --> 00:14:12,002
is very large. It's very clear where one instance begins and

298
00:14:12,022 --> 00:14:16,925
where another ends. This fall is going to take quite a while,

299
00:14:16,945 --> 00:14:22,429
but basically it repeats. So we're going to continue on. Let's

300
00:14:22,449 --> 00:14:26,211
just watch it through. Okay, we've landed.

301
00:14:26,922 --> 00:14:31,026
Now, when I introduced world wrapping, it created a lot of

302
00:14:31,086 --> 00:14:34,148
unexpected solutions to previous problems, which is very nice.

303
00:14:35,329 --> 00:14:38,692
This is an image by M.C. Escher, a cubic space division.

304
00:14:39,653 --> 00:14:44,316
And the original inspiration for the game was I wanted to

305
00:14:44,356 --> 00:14:47,199
make a game based on M.C. Escher's works, and I wanted to

306
00:14:47,239 --> 00:14:48,220
put this level in the game.

307
00:14:49,200 --> 00:14:51,242
Now, here's an implementation of it in July 2013.

308
00:14:51,422 --> 00:14:53,904
So this was before world wrapping got added.

309
00:14:54,801 --> 00:14:57,082
World wrapping got added about a year and a half into the development.

310
00:14:58,163 --> 00:15:02,546
Now when I made this level without world wrapping it was actually very painful to play so

311
00:15:03,447 --> 00:15:06,869
the game, the level basically consisted of all these lattices that repeated

312
00:15:07,469 --> 00:15:07,930
and you

313
00:15:08,370 --> 00:15:10,511
went in and you just had to find an exit. So very simple.

314
00:15:11,619 --> 00:15:14,742
But the problem was, it was very hard to orient yourself

315
00:15:14,782 --> 00:15:18,326
because everything, basically all parts of the level

316
00:15:18,366 --> 00:15:20,728
looked the same, and also if you fell off

317
00:15:20,748 --> 00:15:23,070
the lattice structure, you landed on the floor.

318
00:15:23,110 --> 00:15:25,833
And there was a floor because it took place in a room.

319
00:15:27,094 --> 00:15:29,397
And then it was just like very tedious walk

320
00:15:29,617 --> 00:15:30,798
to get back up to a lattice.

321
00:15:32,840 --> 00:15:36,663
Another problem was that in order to make the level look

322
00:15:36,703 --> 00:15:40,966
interesting it had to have a certain scale. But any increase

323
00:15:41,006 --> 00:15:45,649
in scale resulted in an increase in navigational complexity. So

324
00:15:45,689 --> 00:15:48,151
I played it a bit and it just really wasn't fun and I got rid

325
00:15:48,191 --> 00:15:51,673
of it. After I introduced war wrapping all those problems went

326
00:15:51,693 --> 00:15:53,375
away. So this is December 2015.

327
00:15:55,193 --> 00:15:59,896
And now you can see the, so one of those boxes is one instance

328
00:15:59,936 --> 00:16:02,318
of it, and you can go to any of those instances.

329
00:16:02,358 --> 00:16:02,938
It doesn't matter.

330
00:16:03,478 --> 00:16:06,340
So in this case, what happens is it removes,

331
00:16:06,400 --> 00:16:07,941
you do not need to orient yourself.

332
00:16:08,001 --> 00:16:09,442
There is no way, there is literally,

333
00:16:09,582 --> 00:16:11,703
it is literally impossible for the player to get lost

334
00:16:11,763 --> 00:16:13,924
because it doesn't matter which direction you go in,

335
00:16:14,505 --> 00:16:17,306
you are stepping away and also towards the objective.

336
00:16:19,655 --> 00:16:21,956
And it also means that I can increase the scale of it.

337
00:16:22,276 --> 00:16:23,717
In this case, it's basically infinite.

338
00:16:23,997 --> 00:16:26,939
And it doesn't add any navigational complexity.

339
00:16:26,979 --> 00:16:29,561
In fact, it removes a lot of navigational complexity.

340
00:16:30,501 --> 00:16:33,223
And it's also, again, just a much more interesting level

341
00:16:33,243 --> 00:16:34,844
for the player to experience, because this is not something

342
00:16:34,884 --> 00:16:35,864
you see often in games.

343
00:16:36,985 --> 00:16:40,507
Here's another example of something that I wanted to put

344
00:16:40,547 --> 00:16:42,008
in the game before, but couldn't.

345
00:16:42,488 --> 00:16:43,509
These are Indian step wells.

346
00:16:43,569 --> 00:16:45,450
And I saw these, and I thought, well, wouldn't it be amazing

347
00:16:45,490 --> 00:16:46,491
if these just went on forever?

348
00:16:48,055 --> 00:16:50,356
Once I introduced world wrapping, this was impossible.

349
00:16:50,396 --> 00:16:53,097
So in this space, you can keep going down these stairs

350
00:16:53,137 --> 00:16:53,817
or climbing up.

351
00:16:54,797 --> 00:16:56,838
There is an achievement if you get to the bottom.

352
00:16:57,358 --> 00:16:57,538
But.

353
00:16:59,779 --> 00:17:02,020
So what is something that's very interesting about this

354
00:17:02,460 --> 00:17:04,841
is that instead of having the world wrapping happen

355
00:17:04,881 --> 00:17:06,281
on a grid, it is actually offset.

356
00:17:06,361 --> 00:17:10,122
So this is the basic unit that's repeated.

357
00:17:10,342 --> 00:17:11,223
So we have a set of stairs.

358
00:17:11,243 --> 00:17:13,303
Now, if we just have normal world wrapping where

359
00:17:14,681 --> 00:17:18,042
If you go down, if you drop from the bottom right,

360
00:17:18,062 --> 00:17:19,843
you'll come back up down from the bottom left

361
00:17:20,543 --> 00:17:21,924
because we have everything on a grid.

362
00:17:23,465 --> 00:17:24,825
In this infinite step wheel world,

363
00:17:25,566 --> 00:17:26,746
when you drop down from the bottom right,

364
00:17:26,766 --> 00:17:29,247
you actually come back from the upper left.

365
00:17:29,448 --> 00:17:30,988
And the reason why that's happening is because

366
00:17:31,048 --> 00:17:32,269
instead of putting everything on a grid,

367
00:17:32,289 --> 00:17:33,469
we've offset them slightly.

368
00:17:34,110 --> 00:17:36,011
Because when you're going down these stairs,

369
00:17:36,511 --> 00:17:37,591
you're not actually going straight down,

370
00:17:37,611 --> 00:17:39,132
you're going down and forward.

371
00:17:42,051 --> 00:17:44,332
And this is what it looks like when you're climbing up.

372
00:17:46,373 --> 00:17:48,854
And then you can, because of the gravity rotation mechanic,

373
00:17:48,894 --> 00:17:52,315
you can also choose to just fall down the level from the side.

374
00:17:54,276 --> 00:17:56,076
Now, of course, adding roll wrapping

375
00:17:56,096 --> 00:17:57,877
also introduced a lot of new problems.

376
00:17:59,118 --> 00:18:00,258
One of the problems is gating.

377
00:18:00,758 --> 00:18:02,139
Basically, when the player is outside,

378
00:18:02,159 --> 00:18:03,819
the entire level pretty much opens up.

379
00:18:04,900 --> 00:18:05,500
You can go anywhere.

380
00:18:05,520 --> 00:18:07,261
And everyone would say, isn't there,

381
00:18:08,001 --> 00:18:09,762
can't the player just skip all these levels

382
00:18:09,802 --> 00:18:10,402
and get to the end?

383
00:18:11,576 --> 00:18:11,876
And yeah.

384
00:18:13,257 --> 00:18:15,839
So this is, let's talk about the 2D example.

385
00:18:15,899 --> 00:18:18,341
So in this level we want the player to get to the star.

386
00:18:18,361 --> 00:18:20,662
And what we'll do, this is too easy,

387
00:18:20,722 --> 00:18:22,303
so we'll put a wall here.

388
00:18:23,044 --> 00:18:25,545
And now maybe the player's gotta go get a key

389
00:18:25,605 --> 00:18:28,767
to open the lock, or they have to learn double jump.

390
00:18:29,508 --> 00:18:38,626
When you introduce wall wrapping, though, that wall is no longer a barrier because the player can jump to the right and land back on the other side, or they can jump down and come back down from above.

391
00:18:39,067 --> 00:18:41,331
And the reason why that's happening is because of the repetitions.

392
00:18:44,462 --> 00:18:47,383
and now I actually got, so this caused a problem with pacing

393
00:18:47,423 --> 00:18:50,384
for a long time until I played Skyrim, and in Skyrim,

394
00:18:50,944 --> 00:18:53,224
when you are outside, you can get to anywhere on the map,

395
00:18:53,704 --> 00:18:55,085
but then once you go inside a dungeon,

396
00:18:55,105 --> 00:18:57,185
it becomes a very linear experience,

397
00:18:57,205 --> 00:19:00,106
so the game is open exploration and linear adventuring.

398
00:19:01,526 --> 00:19:03,187
And I actually took that for my game,

399
00:19:03,247 --> 00:19:04,607
so when you are outside in the space,

400
00:19:04,647 --> 00:19:05,587
I allow you to go anywhere.

401
00:19:07,347 --> 00:19:08,468
I just sort of embrace that.

402
00:19:08,848 --> 00:19:10,729
But then there are these islands with puzzles,

403
00:19:10,769 --> 00:19:12,550
and once you get there, then it's a linear path.

404
00:19:12,650 --> 00:19:14,671
And once you're indoor, you can't whirlwrap,

405
00:19:14,711 --> 00:19:17,173
so that removes the problem of players skipping areas.

406
00:19:18,033 --> 00:19:20,274
Another problem you'll find is that height and direction

407
00:19:20,314 --> 00:19:22,015
basically become meaningless

408
00:19:22,135 --> 00:19:23,896
once you introduce weird geometry.

409
00:19:23,916 --> 00:19:28,059
A lot of games will have something like a tower, right?

410
00:19:28,119 --> 00:19:29,320
And you might get a mission that's

411
00:19:29,960 --> 00:19:31,121
meet me at the base of the tower.

412
00:19:32,118 --> 00:19:33,479
So let's go back to our 2D example.

413
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:38,102
If I were to ask you where the star is, you'd say it's near

414
00:19:38,122 --> 00:19:39,403
the base of the tower to the left.

415
00:19:40,464 --> 00:19:41,765
Once you introduce war wrapping, though, that

416
00:19:42,125 --> 00:19:44,266
direction doesn't really make sense because the star is also

417
00:19:44,306 --> 00:19:45,207
to the right of the tower.

418
00:19:46,249 --> 00:19:49,631
And now what if we started to decrease the distance between

419
00:19:49,731 --> 00:19:54,354
the instances so that they start touching each other. So now in

420
00:19:54,394 --> 00:19:57,115
this case, base of the tower doesn't make sense because this

421
00:19:57,156 --> 00:20:01,318
tower does not have a base. It's disconnected. This is one

422
00:20:01,358 --> 00:20:05,560
implementation of it in manifold garden. And here you can see

423
00:20:05,580 --> 00:20:08,322
this is literally a building without a base.

424
00:20:11,570 --> 00:20:13,992
So once you introduce war wrapping, a lot of things,

425
00:20:14,132 --> 00:20:15,734
you know, words like northeast, southwest,

426
00:20:15,794 --> 00:20:19,017
up, down, left, right, that we use for directions,

427
00:20:19,157 --> 00:20:20,638
they get tossed out the window.

428
00:20:21,579 --> 00:20:24,101
Now what I found is you want to embrace the problems.

429
00:20:24,441 --> 00:20:26,002
So you want to design with the geometry

430
00:20:26,163 --> 00:20:26,843
instead of against it.

431
00:20:27,284 --> 00:20:28,725
For example, what works really well is

432
00:20:28,965 --> 00:20:30,566
designing your levels to be radial,

433
00:20:31,047 --> 00:20:33,189
thinking of something as inside and then outside

434
00:20:33,229 --> 00:20:34,770
and allowing the players to get there

435
00:20:35,110 --> 00:20:36,852
between these two places from any directions

436
00:20:37,392 --> 00:20:37,912
instead of...

437
00:20:39,402 --> 00:20:41,983
This is much better than having something that's just a single

438
00:20:42,023 --> 00:20:45,125
direction. I just put directional as a word for this.

439
00:20:47,166 --> 00:20:49,827
Now what I want to talk about now is a number of techniques

440
00:20:49,927 --> 00:20:52,988
that I found to have worked well. And these fall under two

441
00:20:53,008 --> 00:20:53,568
categories.

442
00:20:55,629 --> 00:20:58,131
The first is macro, which has to deal with the big picture,

443
00:20:58,211 --> 00:20:59,451
the way you organize your level.

444
00:21:00,092 --> 00:21:02,113
And the second is micro, the second group of techniques

445
00:21:02,133 --> 00:21:04,274
is micro, which deal more with moment to moment,

446
00:21:04,934 --> 00:21:06,615
not necessarily when the player is stopping to think,

447
00:21:06,635 --> 00:21:08,076
but when they're moving through levels,

448
00:21:08,136 --> 00:21:10,397
how can you help them, how can you help guide them?

449
00:21:11,798 --> 00:21:13,879
So in macro, you want to have an iconic party.

450
00:21:14,159 --> 00:21:16,460
The word party is the layout of a building.

451
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:17,881
I got that from Robert Yang's

452
00:21:19,382 --> 00:21:20,782
level design histories talk last year,

453
00:21:20,822 --> 00:21:21,743
which I highly recommend.

454
00:21:22,403 --> 00:21:23,844
And you want to have logic to your level.

455
00:21:24,796 --> 00:21:27,417
and with micro you want to have intentional architecture and

456
00:21:27,437 --> 00:21:30,719
you want to utilize patterns and architectural elements. So let's

457
00:21:30,739 --> 00:21:32,860
talk about the first macro technique, iconic parties. So

458
00:21:32,900 --> 00:21:34,921
these are some examples of architectural parties. You've

459
00:21:34,941 --> 00:21:37,263
got the layout. This is kind of roughly what the building looks

460
00:21:37,283 --> 00:21:40,664
like. When you're designing a game based on M.C. Escher's work

461
00:21:40,704 --> 00:21:43,046
it's very tempting to kind of overwhelm the player with a lot

462
00:21:43,086 --> 00:21:46,107
of staircases and tunnels and weird stuff. And I think that

463
00:21:46,127 --> 00:21:48,389
works very well in a print because you kind of want to, you

464
00:21:48,409 --> 00:21:50,890
know, look at it in detail and discover things you didn't see

465
00:21:50,930 --> 00:21:51,270
before.

466
00:21:52,758 --> 00:21:54,379
However, this does not work well in a level.

467
00:21:54,999 --> 00:21:57,921
So this is my very first attempt

468
00:21:58,181 --> 00:21:59,461
at the opening level of the world.

469
00:21:59,501 --> 00:22:00,922
And you can see I was just putting staircases

470
00:22:00,962 --> 00:22:01,623
and tunnels everywhere.

471
00:22:01,643 --> 00:22:04,184
And it looks and feels very MCS-sure.

472
00:22:04,224 --> 00:22:05,225
This is another example.

473
00:22:05,605 --> 00:22:06,865
But if you were to draw,

474
00:22:06,905 --> 00:22:10,087
if you were to ask me what the party of this level is,

475
00:22:10,187 --> 00:22:11,508
well, this is what it is.

476
00:22:11,588 --> 00:22:12,248
It's very messy.

477
00:22:12,288 --> 00:22:15,610
There's no clear structure to it.

478
00:22:16,923 --> 00:22:18,364
This is the same level now.

479
00:22:18,665 --> 00:22:20,346
And you can see in this case what we have

480
00:22:20,566 --> 00:22:23,709
is a central tower surrounded by four islands.

481
00:22:25,871 --> 00:22:27,213
And what's really great about this shape

482
00:22:27,273 --> 00:22:29,295
is you can see that from any direction.

483
00:22:29,735 --> 00:22:31,096
And also with the world wrapping,

484
00:22:31,477 --> 00:22:33,839
you can see the repetitions of it in the distance.

485
00:22:33,859 --> 00:22:35,300
So I don't have a mini map in the world.

486
00:22:36,261 --> 00:22:38,844
However, because you can see the repetition of the world,

487
00:22:40,008 --> 00:22:43,010
from where you are, you can, by looking at the other instances,

488
00:22:43,050 --> 00:22:44,771
you can figure out what the current shape,

489
00:22:45,472 --> 00:22:46,832
what the current structure of your world is.

490
00:22:47,193 --> 00:22:50,435
And so it helps if you have a very clear design instead

491
00:22:50,475 --> 00:22:51,055
of just a mess.

492
00:22:53,657 --> 00:22:56,559
So a comparison of how the levels changed.

493
00:22:57,240 --> 00:23:00,142
And these are examples of levels with very clear parity.

494
00:23:00,162 --> 00:23:01,683
Like you can see this one, and right away

495
00:23:02,003 --> 00:23:04,184
you see that these are stairs that continue on forever.

